##### DVD-ROM

In 1995, a powerful consortium of manufacturers—comprising Sony, Philips, [Toshiba](/Toshiba), and [Panasonic](/Panasonic)—collectively developed the second generation of the optical disc, which they aptly named the [DVD](/DVD). The [DVD](/DVD) disc emerged onto the technological landscape after the [CD-ROM](/CD-ROM) had already achieved widespread adoption in society. It was, in essence, the next logical step in the evolution of consumer media and data storage, arriving with an air of inevitability.

#### Third-generation

Third-generation optical discs were specifically engineered for the distribution of [high-definition video](/HDTV) and sophisticated videogames, necessitating significantly greater data storage capacities. This leap in capacity was achieved through the deployment of shorter-wavelength visible-light lasers and optics with larger [numerical apertures](/Numerical_aperture). Both the [Blu-ray Disc](/Blu-ray_Disc) and [HD DVD](/HD_DVD) formats, for instance, utilize [blue-violet lasers](/Blue-violet_lasers) and focusing optics of greater aperture. This allows them to interact with discs featuring even smaller pits and lands, thereby dramatically increasing the data storage capacity per layer. A rather elegant solution, if you ask me, to the relentless demand for more.

In practical terms, the effective capacity for multimedia presentation on these discs is further enhanced by sophisticated video [data compression](/Data_compression) [codecs](/Codec), such as [H.264/MPEG-4 AVC](/H.264/MPEG-4_AVC) and [VC-1](/VC-1). It's not just about fitting more data; it's about making that data smaller to begin with.

