##### Blu-ray and HD-DVD

The third generation of optical discs saw its primary development between 2000 and 2006, culminating in the formal introduction of the [Blu-ray Disc](/Blu-ray_Disc). The first movies released on [Blu-ray Discs](/Blu-ray_Disc) hit the market in June 2006, marking the official start of a rather contentious era. [Blu-ray](/Blu-ray) eventually emerged victorious in the protracted and often acrimonious [high definition optical disc format war](/High_definition_optical_disc_format_war), decisively triumphing over its primary competitor, the [HD DVD](/HD_DVD). A standard [Blu-ray disc](/Blu-ray_disc) can accommodate approximately 25 [gigabytes](/Gigabyte) of data, while a [DVD](/DVD) holds around 4.7 [gigabytes](/Gigabyte), and a [CD](/Compact_disc) a mere 700 [megabytes](/Megabyte). The difference in capacity alone was, as they say, illuminating.

#### Comparison of various optical storage media

#### Fourth-generation

The following formats represent an ambitious leap beyond the current third-generation discs, exhibiting the potential to store in excess of one [terabyte](/Terabyte) (1 [TB](/Terabyte)) of data. At least some of these are explicitly designed for the rather unglamorous, yet critical, task of cold [data storage](/Computer_data_storage) within sprawling [data centers](/Data_centers). A dubious claim, perhaps, but one worth considering.

*   [Archival Disc](/Archival_Disc)

**Announced but abandoned:**

*   [Holographic Versatile Disc](/Holographic_Versatile_Disc)

**Announced but not released:**

*   [LS-R](/LS-R)
*   Protein-coated disc
*   [Stacked Volumetric Optical Disc](/Stacked_Volumetric_Optical_Disc)
*   5D DVD
*   [3D optical data storage](/3D_optical_data_storage) (not a singular technology, but rather a category encompassing examples like [Hyper CD-ROM](/Hyper_CD-ROM) and [Fluorescent Multilayer Disc](/Fluorescent_Multilayer_Disc))

In 2004, development commenced on the ambitious [Holographic Versatile Disc](/Holographic_Versatile_Disc) (HVD), which held the tantalizing promise of storing several [terabytes](/Terabyte) of data on a single disc. Unfortunately, this promising development largely stagnated towards the latter half of the 2000s, primarily due to a lamentable lack of adequate funding. A familiar story, really.

In 2006, reports emerged from Japanese researchers detailing their development of ultraviolet ray lasers with a remarkably short wavelength of 210 [nanometers](/Nanometre). This breakthrough, it was claimed, would enable a significantly higher [bit](/Bit) density than even [Blu-ray discs](/Blu-ray_Disc) could achieve. As of 2022, however, no further updates on that particular project have been reported. One can only assume it's still somewhere in the quantum ether.

